Bali.
The toll road between Tanjung Benoa to Airport and from Airport to Serangan, all in direct line (not curve) is 12.7 kilometers and is equipped also with motorcycle lanes. The toll road is formally opened on September 23, 2013, about a week before APEC Summit in Bali is opened.
Railways.
The majority of Indonesia's railway length is on Java, which has two major rail lines running the length of the island, as well as several minor lines. Passenger and freight services run on these lines. There is also commuter rail service in the Jakarta metropolitan area, known as KRL Jabotabek and in Surabaya.
In 2008, the government (under PT Kereta Api and Angkasa Pura) planned to build an airport rail-link from Soekarno-Hatta Airport to Manggarai (Jakarta), but the project was not started until late 2013. A monorail mass transit system was under construction in Jakarta, but development ceased on 2004 due to lack of fundings, but on October 2013, groundbreaking was done, and the project has started again, which is scheduled to operate on 2016-2017. A mass rapid transit (MRT) system is under construction in Jakarta, which is scheduled to operate on 2018.
The only other areas in Indonesia having railroads are three separate regions of Sumatra, one in the north around Medan, second in the West Sumatra from Pariaman to Padang and the other in the southern trip, from Lubuk Linggau (South Sumatra) to Bandar Lampung, (Lampung).
There are no new railways in Sumatra, except new railways from Medan to the new Kuala Namu International Airport which operates since July 2013. The railways is very important because the toll road is not yet ready and only takes about 45 minutes go with trains.
The island of Kalimantan has or is to get a 122 km long railway for the transport of coal.
Pipelines.
Crude oil 2,505 km; petroleum products 456 km; natural gas 1,703 km (1989)
Air transport.
Air transportation in Indonesia serves as a critical means of connecting the thousands of islands throughout the archipelago. Between 2009 and 2013 the number of Indonesia's air passengers increased over 43% from 59,384,362 to 85,102,827.
Airports.
Jakarta's Soekarno–Hatta International Airport serves as the country's main air transportation hub. However safety issues continue to be problematic. Several recent accidents have helped make Indonesia's air transport system one of the least safe in the world.
